---

[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I have tried and failed to incorporate 3D Gaussian splats into my VFX workflow. I want all of that high-resolution detail, but I found that the Gaussian splats slowed Blender and Nuke to a halt. I thought I\'d hit a dead end until I found a plugin for Unreal Engine'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called Volinga. With it, you can navigate high-resolution splats in real time, relight them as if they\'re a mesh, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; and even edit the materials. It\'s also completely compatible with an ACeS color space workflow. The plugin really feels'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like the backbone of a 3D Gaussian splat workflow. So, let me show you the entire process of going from a raw PLY file into a final composite. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; When you\'re in Unreal Engine, you are going to first install the Volinga'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'plugin. So, just go to edit, plugins, search for Volinga, and then activate it, and then it\'s going to ask you to restart Unreal Engine. So, do that, and then restart. You\'ll see the Volinga'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'plugin up here. And then the next thing you\'re going to need to do is add your license. Currently, you have to have an actual Volinga asset. And so, I have one here. You\'re just going to drop that'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into your content browser. Then when you open this licensing panel, I will just take this license, drag it up here into this array element, hit save, and then Volinga will work. You can set your'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Unreal project to ACeS, and Volinga will work within that ACeS color space. I\'m going to be using a 3D Gaussian splat provided by Megascapes, and they processed this Gaussian splat as RGB. So, I\'m going to keep my Unreal project'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as sRGB. To use a 3D Gaussian splat in Unreal Engine, you do need some type of plugin. When you\'re using Volinga, you can just drag and drop that splat into your content browser, and it\'s going to auto-generate an ENVOL file. And then'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can just drag and drop that file right into the timeline. This splat comes in a little bit rotated, so I\'m going to rotate it 90° on the Y axis. That\'s looking correct. Uh I also'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'noticed that the streets of this alley are kind of like 45° off from the grid on the floor. So, I\'m just going to rotate on the Z axis about 45° to get everything lined up. This is a pretty'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'massive 3D Gaussian splat that Mega Scapes did. Uh this is an alleyway in Toronto at night and it has uh this whole intersection and down a few of the streets. And as you\'re kind of exploring'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this splat in Unreal Engine, one of the things that you\'ll notice is that this is all in real time. Like it\'s absolutely nothing uh just navigating around. So, there are a couple of settings in the Volinga'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'plugin here in this drop-down. And one is going to be the ambient light. It\'s set to one. Uh we can bring that down a little bit cuz we\'re going to be adding light. So, let\'s bring that to like 0.2 and that\'s going to darken the whole'

[02:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scene. But what\'s really cool is you\'ll notice that uh all of the kind of bright spots on the splat of the street lights stay bright. It\'s not just dimming the entire thing down, uh which is really helpful to kind of create this darker,'

[02:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'moodier atmosphere that we can then add some light on top of. So, now let\'s go in and add an actor. So, let\'s add a just do like a point light. Uh bring this in. I\'m going to adjust some'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'settings here. You can kind of already see it uh interacting with the light. I\'m going to change it to a red color so it\'s, you know, noticeably different from uh the light in the scene and then bring up that intensity a bit. And'

[03:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ll see as I move uh this light around that it\'s interacting with this environment pretty well as if it\'s like a mesh. There are a couple of options here in Volinga. There is the estimated'

[03:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'normals, inverse, and then a proxy mesh. We\'ll get to the proxy mesh later, but um some parts of a splat will respond really well to the estimated normals. Some parts of the splat might do a'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little bit better with the um with the inverse. So, you just have to It just depends on where in the splat um you can see in your shot and then what kind of light you have and what'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'direction it\'s coming from. You can toggle between those two. But, now let\'s actually do something with this flat. Volinga is a cool tool, but I\'m interested in how these tools can actually help me achieve some type of creative vision. So, to do that, we\'re'

[04:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to put an actual shot together. So, I have this shot here. Uh this is an actor in front of a green screen uh with some like red and blue flashing lights. Um all of the camera tracking data here'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was done with the virtual production app Jetset by Lightcraft. Adding this Python script here imports the tracked camera, an image plane with the footage, and then also this um mesh that\'s a 3D scan of the actual wall that we have for'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reference where we are shooting. Um so, I\'m going to create a new actor um and bind uh my camera and this mesh to this new actor so that I can move this shot around.'

[04:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I think moving it over here to the intersection makes the most sense uh because then I can kind of have these sort of police lights coming from down one of the streets. And then I\'m going to add, you know, a bright red and bright blue light coming from this'

[05:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'corner over here. It looks pretty good, but one thing you\'ll notice is that it\'s lighting the entire fence over here. It\'s kind of lighting from behind. This is part of what can happen with the'

[05:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'estimated normals um with Volinga. So, I\'m just going to add this cube here, and I\'m just going to try to block out some light and add some shadows using that. So, I\'m just going to quickly kind of scale it. In its materials, I\'m going'

[05:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to change its blend mode to masked, add a shadow pass switch, set the top value to zero and the bottom value to one, and then plug this into alpha mask. And then we won\'t see the actual mesh of the'

[05:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'object itself, but we will have its shadows. Um so this is like a little bit of a kind of creative work around with using the splat. Um but for this case it works super well uh just to kind of create that shadow of the light coming'

[05:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from this other direction. And actually now that I do that, I\'m going to kind of offset the red and blue lights as if like they\'re each on either side of the top of a police car so that as they flash the shadow is a little bit'

[06:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different so it\'s not just the light flashing changing color. Uh I think that\'s going to add to this effect quite well. Now let\'s take the shot even further with the proxy mesh setting in the Volinga plugin. Basically this takes'

[06:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like an actual mesh of your 3D environment and uses that to calculate all of the normals. It also allows you to do some vertex painting to adjust the material itself. I don\'t actually have a uh proxy mesh of the splat. Uh you can'

[06:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generate them when you\'re processing them if you\'re using like Reality Capture. There\'s also tools like MeshLab which can allow you to do it. I found that that wasn\'t working for this one. I think it was maybe just too big. I could'

[06:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have asked Megascans to provide that for me, but I decided I\'m just going to try modeling one myself and see what happens. So here in Unreal Engine, I\'m going to add a uh rectangle for the floor and some cubes and line them up to'

[07:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the walls here. Um and then I\'m just going to merge them all together into one static mesh. It\'s not very detailed. It\'s just cubes, but uh let\'s see let\'s'

[07:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see what happens. Uh when I do get into that vertex painting, it\'s going to use the vertices. So I\'m going to also take the static mesh and remesh it in Unreal Engine to add more vertices to all of'

[07:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the surfaces. Then to get this all set up, we\'re going to add a Volinga mesh. And then here in the static mesh setting, we\'re just going to drag our static mesh over here and then line it up to our 3D Gaussian'

[07:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'splat. Then in the Volinga plugin, I\'m going to choose proxy mesh and it\'s going to be using the normals from this mesh that I just created or I you know, a more detailed one. Uh it works fairly well, you know, you'

[07:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can see like very clean crisp shadows from the lights. You\'ll notice that back here in this section, uh it\'s a little off because it\'s not perfectly aligned, but that\'s because this was just a cubes'

[08:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in simple detail. But for this test, let\'s go with it. Now to do some vertex painting, we need to uh set up our material in the static mesh itself. So, we\'re going to add a vertex color node and then we\'re going to plug in the RGB'

[08:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to base color, the R to roughness, the G to emission, and the B to metallic. And this allows us to adjust for all of those. Um I do eventually just turn off the the green channel going into'

[08:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'emission at one point uh just because it was creating this kind of extra glow that I didn\'t need. Um so, feel free to tweak this however you\'d like. But once we save that material, we can go into'

[08:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mesh paint mode, choose paint. We\'re going to do just red here because that is the roughness. So, for color, if we have this all the way black, that means there is no roughness, which means um the surface will be 100% reflective. And'

[08:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if it\'s all the way white, um it\'s going to be 100% rough uh and no reflection at all. Um so, usually things aren\'t all the way black or all the way white, um but we\'re going to you know, adjust our'

[09:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'color a little bit and then we\'re also going to adjust the intensity of our brush. But if we make this black and then start painting right here on the surface, um you can see that suddenly we have this um shiny streak that looks a'

[09:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lot like uh it\'s the ground is wet or something. This is a lot of fun and makes for a lot of creative control, which is cool. It also, you know, allows you to treat a 3D Gaussian splat as if'

[09:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it is an actual mesh itself um and do things like this to change the environment uh the way you need to change it for your shot while maintaining all of that detail of the splat itself. Another thing that I\'m'

[09:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to add here is I\'m going to go back to the material and add a noise node and a normal from height map node. That\'s going to give the surface some more imperfections as well. And then um'

[10:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m going to set up some some lights in the background here, some actual like lights in the in the Unreal Engine scene exactly where they would be in the 3D Gaussian splat so I can see some reflection in that water, like a'

[10:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'brighter reflection, and get some of that parallax as the camera moves. And now it\'s time to render out the passes. I\'ve done this kind of flashing light effect before uh where in Blender I have animated a light to match the light that'

[10:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we had on our actor. Um and for the most part it works really well, but one thing that I ran into was every couple flashes, you know, the background and foreground would be just slightly offset. Um and so instead of uh running'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into that problem, especially because these flashing lights it was an aperture and finobar in like one of their, you know, special settings of police lights. It\'s not the same brightness every'

[10:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'single flash. So I\'m actually going to render out the shot with no lighting, with the red light on the entire time, and then with the blue light on the entire time, and just do a crossfade. But that allows me to have full control'

[11:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the compositing process that allows for some more finesse than here in Unreal Engine. So I\'m going to bring this all into Nuke. I have my shot here. I\'m going to key out our actor and do a little bit of roto. Then I\'m going to'

[11:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'drop that on top of my background here. Then I can render this out of Nuke, bring it into DaVinci to do a final color grade. And here is our final shot. Volingo really unlocked the 3D Gaussian'

[11:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Splat workflow for me. I know with Volinga and Unreal Engine, it\'s not just for VFX. You can go straight into a virtual production workflow and an interactive gaming environment [music]'

[11:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'workflow as well. So, check out Volinga and let me know your thoughts.'
